6 AS INTRODUCED
7 An Act relating to state government; amending 74 O.S.
2021, Section 5060.26, which relates to the Oklahoma
8 Alliance for Manufacturing Excellence; modifying
composition of board of directors; providing an
9 effective date; and declaring an emergency.
10
11
12
13 BE IT ENACTED BY THE PEOPLE OF THE STATE OF OKLAHOMA:
14 SECTION 1. AMENDATORY 74 O.S. 2021, Section 5060.26, is
15 amended to read as follows:
16 Section 5060.26. A. A private, not-for-profit corporation may
17 be organized pursuant to the provisions of Title 18 of the Oklahoma
18 Statutes and the provisions of this act to develop the Industrial
19 Extension System in Oklahoma, with a special emphasis on minority
20 business enterprises. Such corporation, upon certification by
21 Oklahoma Futures, shall be known as and may exercise all of the
22 powers of OAME.
23 B. In addition to the provisions and requirements of Title 18
24 of the Oklahoma Statutes, the certificate of incorporation and the
Req. No. 10192 Page 1
1 byla ws of OAME must be certified by Oklahoma Futures and the
2 certificate of incorporation shall:
3 1. Designate the name of the corporation as the Oklahoma
4 Alliance for Manufacturing Excellence, Inc.;
5 2. Provide that the exclusive purposes of OAME are public
6 purposes to assist small and medium-sized manufacturing firms, with
7 a special emphasis on minority business enterprises, to gain the
8 ability, through education, technology transfer, and otherwise, to
9 compete successfully at progressively higher levels of value-added
10 in the national and international economy;
11 3. Provide for the following three classes of membership in
12 OAME which shall have representation on the Board of Directors of
13 OAME:
14 a. one class composed of small and medium-sized
15 manufacturing firms located in Oklahoma, and the
16 certificate of incorporation shall provide for the
17 qualifications for membership in such class,
18 b. one class composed of large corporations, and the
19 certificate of incorporation shall provide for the
20 qualifications for membership in such class, and
21 c. one class composed of state entities, including, but
22 not limited to, the Oklahoma Center for the
23 Advancement of Science and Technology, the Oklahoma
24 Department of Commerce, the Oklahoma Department of
Req. No. 10192 Page 2
1 Career and Technology Education, and the Oklahoma
2 State Regents for Higher Education;
3 4. Provide for classes of associate membership which shall not
4 have representation on the Board of Directors of OAME, except as
5 provided in paragraph 5 of this subsection;
6 5. Provide that the Board of Directors of OAME shall consist of
7 five nine representatives of members who shall be individuals
8 elected at the first annual meeting of OAME by members of the class
9 composed of small and medium-sized manufacturing firms, and four
10 representatives of members who shall be individuals elected at the
11 first annual meeting of OAME by members of the class composed of
12 large corporations. The Board of Directors also shall include the
13 President following state governmental representatives as ex officio
14 members: the Executive Director of the Oklahoma Center for the
15 Advancement of Science and Technology, the Executive Director of a
16 designee from the Oklahoma Department of Commerce, the Director of
17 and a designee from the Oklahoma Department of Career and Technology
18 Education and the Chancellor of Higher Education as ex officio
19 members (CareerTech). The bylaws of OAME may provide for designees
20 who may serve in the place of any of the directors and the terms
21 under which any such designation will be made. The Board of
22 Directors shall have the power to elect, from time to time, persons
23 to serve as directors who are associate members or are not
24 affiliated with any entity or firm which qualifies for membership in
Req. No. 10192 Page 3
1 OAME , provided that no more than three (3) one of such persons shall
2 serve on the Board of Directors at any time;
3 6. Have the authority to set membership dues in an amount to be
4 determined by the Board of Directors. No participating state entity
5 shall pay membership dues;
6 7. Provide for all powers necessary or appropriate to carry out
7 and effectuate its corporate purposes, including, but not limited
8 to, the following:
9 a. to maintain an office at such place or places as it
10 may designate,
11 b. to make and execute contracts with any individual,
12 corporation, association or any other entity and all
13 other instruments necessary or convenient for the
14 performance of its duties and the exercise of its
15 powers and functions under this act,
16 c. to receive funds from any source to carry out the
17 purposes of this act, including, but not limited to,
18 gifts or grants from any department, agency or
19 instrumentality of the United States or of the state
20 for any purpose consistent with the provisions of this
21 act,
22 d. to acquire or sell, convey, lease, exchange, transfer
23 or otherwise dispose of its property or any interest
24 therein,
Req. No. 10192 Page 4
1 e. to develop plans and policies to assist small and
2 medium-sized manufacturing companies in Oklahoma,
3 f. to enter into contracts to provide assistance to small
4 and medium-sized manufacturing companies, including,
5 but not limited to, the following categories:
6 (1) technology,
7 (2) human resources development,
8 (3) market planning,
9 (4) finance, and
10 (5) inter-firm collaboration,
11 g. to assist other organizations providing general
12 business assistance to small and medium-sized
13 manufacturing enterprises,
14 h. to establish manufacturing quality and standards
15 certification programs, setting minimum standards and
16 issuing certification to companies meeting such
17 standards,
18 i. to develop and distribute information about
19 manufacturing modernization and assistance that is
20 available to support efforts to improve the abilities
21 of small and medium-sized firms to produce and market
22 higher value-added products,
23
24
Req. No. 10192 Page 5
1 j. to establish a system to evaluate the effectiveness
2 and efficiency of services provided to small and
3 medium-sized manufacturing firms,
4 k. to establish and operate, directly or under contract,
5 an information system designed to access resources
6 that will assist the firms to become more productive,
7 l. establish a training program for individuals working
8 on behalf of small and medium-sized manufacturing
9 firms, and
10 m. to establish special educational and informational
11 programs for its members.
12 SECTION 2. This act shall become effective July 1, 2025.
13 SECTION 3. It being immediately necessary for the preservation
14 of the public peace, health or safety, an emergency is hereby
15 declared to exist, by reason whereof this act shall take effect and
16 be in full force from and after its passage and approval.
